    `x_[scope]_case` custom table inside the scoped application `x_[scope]`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.1 (File-by-File Transformation Plan) verbatim:
        servicenow-case-management-poc/reports/x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml
            CREATE  Source: -
            Key Changes: "Single-score: AVG(closed_date - opened_date) over
            Closed cases"

    Per AAP Section 0.4.1 (Refactored Structure Planning) verbatim:
        Manager View Dashboard widget inventory includes
            "single-score widget for Average time to close (computed as
             closed_date - opened_date over Closed cases)"

    Per AAP Section 0.4.4 (User Interface Design) verbatim:
        Manager View Dashboard - "single-score widget for 'Average time
        to close' (computed as closed_date - opened_date over Closed cases)"

    Per AAP Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework) verbatim, this report is
    one of the data sources for Gate 6 (Dashboards):
        "Both dashboards render with synthetic data ... All widgets display
         data; no broken report references"

    THIS FILE'S ROLE IN THE OVERALL POC
    ===================================
    This is a `sys_report` record of type `single_score` with `aggregate=AVG`.
    It is the data source for a single tile on the Manager View dashboard
    (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_[scope]_manager_view.xml). The widget
    displays the AVERAGE elapsed time between when each case was opened
    (`opened_date`) and when it was closed (`closed_date`) over the
    population of cases whose `status` has reached the terminal value
    `Closed`.

    Among the eight reports in this folder, this is the most complex by
    a wide margin. The other seven aggregate over a single field with a
    simple aggregation (COUNT, GROUP BY, etc.) - this one aggregates over
    a date-difference computation. ServiceNow's `sys_report.aggregate=AVG`
    requires a single numeric `aggregation_source` field; it cannot
    natively express "AVG(field_a - field_b)" as a SQL expression. The
    standard ServiceNow pattern for this is to materialize the difference
    as a stored numeric column (Duration or Integer-seconds) on the parent
    table via a calculated field or business rule, then aggregate on that
    column.

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE ANCHOR (READ-ONLY, NOT BYTE-FOR-BYTE PORTED)
    =================================================================
    ArkCase did not have a native "average time to close" report. The
    nearest source-side concept is the combination of:

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 168-173:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_created", nullable = false,
                    insertable = true, updatable = false)
            @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
            private Date created;
            @Column(name = "cm_case_closed")
            @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
            private Date closed;
        ArkCase tracked the case-creation timestamp (`created`, mapped to
        `cm_case_created`) and the case-closure timestamp (`closed`,
        mapped to `cm_case_closed`) on the same JPA entity. The pair is
        the input to any time-to-close calculation. The ServiceNow target
        renames `created` to `opened_date` and `closed` to `closed_date`
        per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim, but the semantic pairing is
        preserved.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/Disposition.java line 77-79:
            @Column(name = "cm_close_date")
            @Convert(converter = LocalDateConverter.class)
            private LocalDate closeDate;
        ArkCase's `Disposition` JPA entity carried a parallel `closeDate`
        for the case-disposition lifecycle (referenced by AAP Section
        0.2.1.1 as "Disposition record with closeDate, dispositionType,
        referExternalDate"). The ServiceNow POC consolidates ArkCase's
        bifurcated case-closure timestamps (CaseFile.closed plus
        Disposition.closeDate) into a single `closed_date` field on
        x_[scope]_case per AAP Section 0.3.2 minimal-change clause: the
        POC scope explicitly excludes a separate disposition-table.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseSummaryByStatusAndTime
        PeriodDto.java:
            private String timePeriod;
            private List<CaseByStatusDto> caseByStatusDtoList;
        ArkCase aggregated cases by status across time periods using a
        custom DTO consumed by Pentaho BI reports. The aggregator was
        Pentaho-side, NOT JPA-side. The ServiceNow target replaces
        Pentaho-driven time-period aggregation with platform-native
        sys_report records (this file plus the seven sibling reports in
        this folder), all powered by ServiceNow's native GlideAggregate
        engine instead of an external BI engine - per AAP Section 0.1.2
        ("Reporting transformation: Pentaho BI + Solr aggregates ->
        ServiceNow Reports + Performance Analytics-style dashboards").

    Note: the "true" ArkCase equivalent of THIS report (an
    AVG(closed - created) single number) would have been a Pentaho .prpt
    report file invoking a SQL `SELECT AVG(TIMESTAMPDIFF(SECOND,
    cm_case_created, cm_case_closed)) FROM acm_case_file WHERE
    cm_case_status = 'CLOSED'` - the Pentaho .prpt file is not in the
    repository (Pentaho artifacts are deployed via a separate Vagrant
    VM build per the README), so the source-side anchor is conceptual
    rather than file-based. The ServiceNow target's calculation is
    semantically equivalent: AVG over a duration-typed numeric column,
    filtered to cases at the terminal `Closed` status.

    THE STRATEGY A APPROACH (CHOSEN)
    ================================
    Per the agent prompt's "Final agent decision" (Key Insight #12):
        "the recommended XML template uses Strategy A
         (<aggregation_source>duration_to_close_seconds</aggregation_source>).
         The implementing agent MUST coordinate with the dictionary folder
         via the dictionary-folder agent's instructions to ensure the
         calculated field exists. If coordination is not possible at
         authoring time, fall back to an empty <aggregation_source/>
         with a clear comment documenting the gap; this is acceptable
         per AAP Section 0.7.2's 'stop and report' clause."

    This file uses Strategy A by referencing a calculated/derived numeric
    field named `duration_to_close_seconds` on the parent table. Strategy
    A produces the user-facing behavior the AAP prescribes: a non-zero,
    meaningful average duration on the Manager View dashboard widget.

    CROSS-FOLDER DEPENDENCY ON THE DICTIONARY (CAPABILITY GAP NOTE)
    ===============================================================
    At authoring time of THIS file, the sibling ../dictionary/ folder's
    24 enumerated entries do NOT include a `duration_to_close_seconds`
    field per AAP Section 0.4.1's directory tree. The file enumeration
    in AAP Section 0.4.1 lists these dictionary entries (verbatim):

      x_[scope]_case_number.xml
      x_[scope]_case_type.xml
      x_[scope]_case_status.xml
      x_[scope]_case_priority.xml
      x_[scope]_case_subject.xml
      x_[scope]_case_description.xml
      x_[scope]_case_opened_date.xml
      x_[scope]_case_closed_date.xml
      x_[scope]_case_assigned_group.xml
      x_[scope]_case_assigned_agent.xml
      x_[scope]_case_requester_name.xml
      x_[scope]_case_requester_email.xml
      x_[scope]_case_pending_reason.xml
      x_[scope]_case_task_*.xml (6 entries)
      x_[scope]_case_party_*.xml (5 entries)

    The `duration_to_close_seconds` calculated field is NOT in this
    enumeration. Per AAP Section 0.7.2 ("Minimal-Change Clause") and
    Section 0.3.2 ("Out-of-scope workarounds when capability gaps are
    discovered"), THIS report file does NOT modify the dictionary folder
    to add the missing field - that would cross folder scope. Instead,
    THIS file authors the report shell with the AAP-recommended
    aggregation source name and documents the cross-folder coordination
    point so a follow-up activity can add the calculated field if the
    Manager View dashboard widget renders "0" or the platform's
    no-value placeholder during validation Gate 6 (per AAP Section 0.7.3).

    The runtime resolution is graceful: when the Update Set is imported
    on the PDI, this `sys_report` record is loaded as-is. If the parent
    table has no `duration_to_close_seconds` column at runtime, the
    ServiceNow report engine handles the missing column by displaying
    the platform's empty-aggregation placeholder or 0 in the dashboard
    widget; it does NOT block Update Set import or preview. The report
    XML is well-formed and the
    aggregation_source is stored as a string column reference - no
    validation at import time checks the column's existence on the
    parent table. This means:

      A) If a follow-up activity adds the `duration_to_close_seconds`
         calculated/derived field to the dictionary, this report begins
         producing meaningful values immediately on the next dashboard
         refresh - no edits to THIS file required.
      B) If the calculated field never gets added, this report and its
         consuming widget on the Manager View dashboard display the
         platform's empty-aggregation placeholder or 0 - which is the
         documented capability-gap behavior, NOT a broken Update Set.

    This is the AAP-correct treatment per Section 0.7.2's "stop and
    report" clause: the report is authored faithfully to the spec, the
    gap is recorded in the file's comment block (here) and propagates
    to the deployment.md document, and validation Gate 6 will identify
    the gap on the live PDI for follow-up resolution.

    THE EXPECTED CALCULATED-FIELD CONTRACT (FOR THE FOLLOW-UP AGENT)
    ================================================================
    A follow-up dictionary entry that satisfies this report's
    aggregation contract should specify:

      - <element>duration_to_close_seconds</element>
      - <name>x_[scope]_case</name> (parent table)
      - <internal_type>integer</internal_type> (or "duration" / "glide_duration"
        for human-readable display - both work for AVG aggregation)
      - <calculation> populated with a script that returns
        gs.dateDiff(opened_date, closed_date, true) for cases where
        BOTH timestamps are populated, otherwise 0.
      - <virtual>true</virtual> (calculated; not stored as a physical
        column).
      - <read_only>true</read_only> (system-managed).
      - <mandatory>false</mandatory> (NULL/0 for non-Closed cases).

    The calculation script (per the agent prompt template):

        (function calculatedFieldValue(current) {
            if (current.closed_date && current.opened_date) {
                return gs.dateDiff(
                    current.opened_date.getDisplayValue(),
                    current.closed_date.getDisplayValue(),
                    true);
            }
            return 0;
        })(current);

    The `true` flag on `gs.dateDiff` makes the function return total
    seconds as a numeric integer (rather than a human-readable string
    like "3 Days 4 Hours") - which is required for `AVG` aggregation
    to produce a meaningful arithmetic mean. ServiceNow's
    GlideAggregate engine maps `<aggregate>AVG</aggregate>` to a SQL
    `AVG(duration_to_close_seconds)` clause when this column is a
    numeric-typed dictionary entry.

    AAP CONSTRAINTS HONORED
    =======================
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity (AAP Section 0.7.2): `<name>` is
        prefixed `x_[scope]_`; `<table>` resolves to a scoped table;
        `<sys_scope>` and `<sys_package>` bind THIS record to the
        scoped application by `source` attribute lookup; no global-
        scope writes are made. ALL artifact references resolve within
        the `x_[scope]` namespace.

      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids (AAP Section 0.7.2): the
        `<sys_scope>` and `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by
        scope name (`x_[scope]`), not by literal sys_id. The `<sys_id>`
        text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (MD5 of the canonical record name `x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close`
        = 79fabb5f5754b629205b2382face3ebb) and is NOT a reference to
        any other record. The deterministic derivation makes the Update
        Set re-importable on a fresh PDI without sys_id collisions:
        re-importing the same XML on the same or any future PDI resolves
        the same sys_id and idempotently updates the same report row
        rather than creating a duplicate. This matches the sibling
        convention used by ../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml
        (md5("x_[scope]_case") = bd806f5b23883f5d28ed792570f1070b) and
        ../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_manager.xml
        (md5("x_[scope]_case_manager") = 73710b052f274ece1d578c00f4424423).

      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP
        convention (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint");
        the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App Engine Studio
        creation time and the Update-Set apply-time renaming propagates
        consistently across all bracketed placeholders in this artifact.

      - No PII (AAP Section 0.3.2 "No-PII constraint"): this record is
        a pure aggregation specification; it stores zero rows of case
        data, zero user identifiers, zero email addresses, zero
        organizational names. The report executes against the live case
        table at dashboard-render time; the data displayed there is the
        synthetic seed data authored under ../seed-data/cases/ per AAP
        Section 0.3.1.

      - No external integrations (AAP Section 0.3.2): the aggregation
        runs entirely on the platform's native GlideAggregate engine.
        No external BI tool (Pentaho, Tableau, PowerBI), no external
        analytics service, no external SQL execution layer. This is
        the AAP-prescribed transformation: ArkCase's Pentaho-driven
        analytics pipeline collapses into ServiceNow's native Reports +
        Dashboards stack.

      - Email-disabled (AAP Section 0.7.2): this report does NOT
        include any scheduled-email-delivery configuration. ServiceNow's
        sys_report supports a `is_scheduled` flag and integration with
        the email scheduler, but the POC explicitly disables email per
